    "id": "msme-recovery",
    "category": "Advisory Note · Commercial",
    "color": "#C73828",
    "date": "May 2026",
    "title": "Recovering Delayed Payments: The MSME Route Agra's Businesses Overlook",
    "abstract": "For registered micro and small enterprises, the MSMED Act, 2006 offers a recovery mechanism with compound interest and a statutory deposit condition on appeal — often faster than an ordinary suit for recovery.",
    "body": "<p>Agra's manufacturing economy — footwear, leather goods, handicrafts — runs substantially on credit terms, and substantially on delayed payments. The Micro, Small and Medium Enterprises Development Act, 2006 gives registered suppliers a recovery route that ordinary civil suits cannot match.</p>\n<h4>The statutory advantages</h4>\n<p>Section 16 imposes compound interest, at three times the bank rate notified by the Reserve Bank, from the appointed day. Section 18 permits a reference to the Micro and Small Enterprises Facilitation Council, which proceeds through conciliation and, failing settlement, arbitration. Section 19 requires a buyer challenging the award to deposit seventy-five per cent of the awarded amount before the challenge is entertained — a condition that transforms settlement dynamics.</p>\n<h4>The conditions precedent</h4>\n<p>The supplier must hold a valid Udyam registration, and must have held it at the time of supply. The claim must arise from goods supplied or services rendered — the regime does not extend to every commercial grievance between the parties.</p>\n<p>For an enterprise carrying receivables beyond the statutory period, the reference is frequently the most efficient remedy available — and the least used.</p>\n<p class=\"pub-disclaimer\">This note is for general information only and is not legal advice. Facts of each matter differ; obtain specific advice before acting.</p>"
